n was played between the five teams.\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" | 1925 Stallard Cup Results\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Score\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Round 1\n| 15 Aug <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Ellerslie v Northcote\n| page =14\n| work= [[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume=LXII |issue=19098\n| date = 1925-08-17\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250817.2.136\n| accessdate = 2019-09-16}}</ref>\n|| Northcote|| 3 || Ellerslie || 0 || Victoria Park\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Semi Final\n| 15 Aug <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Northcote V Mangere/Kingsland V Otahuhu\n| page =14\n| work= [[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume=LXII |issue=19104\n| date = 1925-08-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250824.2.125.7\n| accessdate = 2019-09-16}}</ref>\n|| Northcote|| 19 || Mangere || 18 || Carlaw Park # 2 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Semi Final\n| 8 Aug|| Otahuhu|| 11 || Kingsland || 2 || Auckland Domain\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Final\n| 5 Sep <ref>{{cite news \n| title =Matches on Saturday/Otahuhu Defeat Northcote\n| page =12\n| work= [[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume=LXII |issue=19116\n| date = 1925-08-07\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250907.2.129\n| accessdate = 2019-09-16}}</ref>\n|| Otahuhu|| 6 || Northcote || 2 || Carlaw Park \n|-\n|}\n\n==Other Club Matches and Lower Grades==\n===Lower Grades===\nThere were 5 lower grades in 1925, with the Sixth Grade split into A and B divisions as it had been in previous years.\nGrades were made of the following teams with the winning team in bold:\n*'''Second Grade''': City, Devonport, Ellerslie, Kingsland, Mangere, Newton, Ponsonby A, Ponsonby B, '''Richmond''', United Suburbs\n*'''Third Grade''': Athletics, City, Coromandel Old Boys, Devonport, Kingsland, Mangere, Newton, New Lynn, Northcote, Parnell, Point Chevalier, Ponsonby A, Ponsonby B, Otahuhu, '''Richmond''', United Suburbs A, United Suburbs B\n*'''Fourth Grade''': Athletics, City, Marist, Devonport, Ellerslie, Kingsland, Newton, Parnell, Point Chevalier, Ponsonby, Richmond\n*'''Fifth Grade''': Athletic, City, Ellerslie, Marist, New Lynn, Northcote, Parnell, Ponsonby, Richmond\n*'''Sixth Grade A''': Athletics, City A, City B, Devonport, Ellerslie, Leys Institute, Marist, Newton, Northcote, Point Chevalier, Ponsonby, '''Richmond''' (unbeaten season)\n*'''Sixth Grade B''': Athletics, City, Ellerslie, Northcote, Point Chevalier, '''Richmond''', United Suburbs\n\n===Exhibition Matches===\nOn 19 April, when Marist had a bye in the first round of the club competition they travelled to Christchurch and played Marist of Christchurch. They won by 16 points to 7. The match also marked the opening of Monica Park.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland v Christchurch/Southern Team Defeated\n| page =4\n| work= [[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume=LXII |issue=18997\n| date = 1925-04-20\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250420.2.7.2\n| accessdate = 2019-09-11}}</ref>\n======Exhibition Match======\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 19 April\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Marist (Christchurch)\n| score = 7-16\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Marist Old Boys Match/Southern Team Defeated\n| page = 4\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 18997\n| date = 1925-04-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250420.2.7.2\n| accessdate = 2019-12-09}}</ref>\n| away = Marist (Auckland)\n| try1 = Petersen\n| con1 = Ellis\n| pen1 = Ellis\n| try2 = [[Jack Kirwan (rugby league)|Jack Kirwan]], Carroll, Gallagher, [[Andrew O\u2019Brien (rugby)|Jim O\u2019Brien]]\n| con2 = [[Charles Gregory (rugby league)|Charles Gregory]]\n| pen2 = [[Charles Gregory (rugby league)|Charles Gregory]]\n| stadium = Monica Park, Christchurch\n| attendance =\n| referee =\n}}\n \n======Labour Day Carnival======\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 25 Oct\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Ponsonby\n| score = 26-16\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Ponsonby Defeat Marist/Twenty Six to Sixteen\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19158\n| date = 1925-10-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19251026.2.115.2\n| accessdate = 2019-12-09}}</ref>\n| away = Marist\n| try1 = [[Frank Delgrosso]] 2, McNeil, [[Tim Peckham]], Payne, [[George Gardiner (rugby league)|George Gardiner]]\n| con1 = [[Frank Delgrosso]] 4\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = [[Hec Brisbane]], [[Arthur Singe]], [[Jack Kirwan (rugby league)|Jack Kirwan]], Sweeney\n| con2 = [[Charles Gregory (rugby league)|Charles Gregory]] 2\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Carlaw Park 1\n| attendance = 2000\n| referee =\n}}\n\n==Representative Season==\nThe [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] representative team had a busy season. After a series of 3 trial matches on 27 June both the New Zealand team and Auckland teams were selected. Officials had declared that \"give us fine weather and we will get an attendance of 20,000\". Unfortunately the weather did not oblige and it was in fact described as \"the worst experienced this season ... in one place there was a miniature lake.\" This resulted in a crowd many times smaller, however thousands came into the ground to watch the main match between North Island and South Island, won by the former 27 points to 9.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Minor Trial Games/A Win for South Auckland/Play Marred by the Rain\n| page =12 \n| work= [[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume=LXII |issue=19056\n| date = 1925-06-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250629.2.140.4\n| accessdate = 2019-09-12}}</ref> Auckland then played against the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] team and lost 9 points to 16. Following this they played a Northern Union Challenge Cup match against the holders South Auckland and were victorious by 24 points to 16. After the New Zealand team returned from their tour of [[Australia]] they again played Auckland at [[Carlaw Park]] and they used the experience they had gained to trounce Auckland by 41 points to 17, employing tactics that the Auckland team were not prepared for. Two weeks later Auckland played [[Queensland rugby league team|Queensland]] who were being touted as the finest league team in the world at the time in the first of three matches. They drew the first, before narrowly losing the second and then being well and truly outclassed in the 3rd match by 54 points to 14.\n\n===Representative Fixtures===\nAfter the trial matches were played the New Zealand team was selected by Mr Liversedge, Pearce, and Harding, and 14 Auckland players made the side. They were: C. Dufty, P. Gregory, Lou Brown, A. Brisbane, F. Delgrosso, J. Kirwan, B. Laing, M. Wetherill, W. Wilson-Hall, C. Webb, B. Avery, E. Herring, J. O'Brien, and H. Dixon. The following day S Lowry of Ponsonby was added to the touring side.\n\n======Inter-Island Match======\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 27 June\n| time = 2:45\n| home = North Island\n| score = 27-9\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Minor Trial Games/A Win for South Auckland/Play Marred by the Rain\n| page =12\n| work= [[The New Zealand Herald]] |volume=LXII |issue=19056\n| date = 1925-06-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250629.2.140.4\n| accessdate = 2019-09-12}}</ref>\n| away = South Island\n| try1 = [[Lou Brown (rugby league)|Lou Brown]], [[Ben Davidson (rugby league)|Ben Davidson]], [[Ernie Herring]] 3, [[Horace Dixon]], [[Bert Avery]]\n| con1 = [[Frank Delgrosso]]\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = [[Neil Mouat]]\n| con2 =\n| pen2 = [[Neil Mouat]] 3\n| stadium = Carlaw Park 1\n| attendance = 4000\n| referee = W Ripley\n}}\n\n======Auckland Trial Match======\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 27 June\n| time = 1:30\n| home = Auckland A\n| score = 0-5\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Minor Trial Games/A Win for South Auckland/Play Marred by the